  "preamble": "The shift from the voiced labiodental fricative [v] to the high-back rounded vowel [u] is a form of vocalization. It typically occurs in coda positions where the fricative weakens into a glide [w] and merges with the vocalic nucleus, a common feature in the transition from Latin to Romance and Old English to Middle English.",
  "phoneticEffects": "Vocalization, Lenition, Labialization",
